04289nam a22005175i 9781442622579DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20182015onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814426225797 a10.3138/97814426225792doi  a(DE-B1597)498422  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aBX1378b.K67 2015eb 7aHIS0140002bisacsh04a282.0922231 aKornberg, Jacques, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Pope's Dilemma :bPius XII Faces Atrocities and Genocide in the Second World War /cJacques Kornberg. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2018] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (424 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aGerman and European Studies00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tTHE POPE’S DILEMMA. Pius XII Faces Atrocities and Genocide in the Second World War -- tIntroduction: An Approach to the Controversy -- t1. The Demolition of Pope Pius XII’s Reputation -- t2. The Vatican and Nazi Germany: The 1933 Concordat -- t3. Pius XII and the Second World War: The Catholic Belligerent States -- t4. Pius XII and the Second World War: Poland -- t5. Catholic Anti-Jewish Attitudes: Achille Ratti, Eugenio Pacelli, and Others -- t6. Policies -- t7. The Debate over Pius XII’s Priorities -- tConclusion: Religious Good Trumps Moral Good -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPope Pius XII presided over the Catholic Church during one of the most challenging moments in its history. Elected in early 1939, Pius XII spoke out against war and destruction, but his refusal to condemn Nazi Germany and its allies for mass atrocities and genocide remains controversial almost seventy years after the end of the Second World War.Scholars have blamed Pius’s inaction on anti-communism, antisemitism, a special emotional bond with Germany, or a preference for fascist authoritarianism. Delving deep into Catholic theology and ecclesiology, Jacques Kornberg argues instead that what drove Pius XII was the belief that his highest priority must be to preserve the authority of the Church and the access to salvation that it provided.In The Pope’s Dilemma, Kornberg uses the examples of Pius XII’s immediate predecessors Benedict XV and the Armenian genocide and Pius XI and Fascist Italy, as well as case studies of Pius XII’s wartime policies towards five Catholic countries (Croatia, France, Hungary, Poland, and Slovakia), to demonstrate the consistency with which Pius XII and the Vatican avoided confronting the perpetrators of atrocities and strove to keep Catholics within the Church. By this measure, Pius XII did not betray, but fulfilled his papal role.A meticulous and careful analysis of the career of the twentieth century’s most controversial pope, The Pope’s Dilemma is an important contribution to the ongoing debate about the Catholic Church’s wartime legacy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945). 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xAtrocities. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xReligious aspectsxCatholic Church. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Germany.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060681240uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144262257940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442622579423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442622579.jpg  a978-3-11-060681-2  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles